-- Ping An Insurance, China Life, Merchants, PetroChina: China Equity Preview
-- Bloomberg News
-- 2010-06-24T00:38:13Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-06-23/china-life-insurance-china-merchants-petrochina-china-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following companies may have
 unusual  price changes in China trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses, and share prices are as of the last close.  
 The  Shanghai Composite Index , which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, dropped 18.83, or 0.7 percent, to
2,569.87. The  CSI 300 Index  fell 0.9 percent to 2,758.50.  
 Insurers: China’s insurance premiums rose 36 percent in the
first five months of this year to 673.7 billion yuan ($98.9
billion), Shi Hong, deputy director of the China Insurance
Regulatory Commission’s general office, said at a briefing in
Shanghai yesterday. The nation’s insurers had 4.05 trillion yuan
of outstanding investments at the end of May, an increase of 8.3
percent from the end of last year, Shi said.  
 China Life Insurance Co.  (601628 CH), the biggest insurer,
added 0.1 percent to 25.29 yuan.  Ping An Insurance (Group) Co. 
(601318 CH), the second-biggest, fell 0.7 percent to 46.76 yuan.  
 Shipping companies: Commodity shipping costs measured by
the  Baltic Dry Index  fell 1.3 percent to 2,515 points, extending
their longest losing streak in 14 months.  
 China Cosco Holdings Co.  (601919 CH), the largest container
line, lost 1.8 percent to 9.55 yuan.  China Shipping Container
Lines Co.  (601866 CH) declined 0.5 percent to 3.72 yuan.  
 China Merchants Bank Co.  (600036 CH): The bank won’t
consider more equity financing before 2012, the China Securities
Journal reported today, citing a company capital management plan.
The lender aims to keep its capital adequacy ratio between 10
percent and 12 percent from 2010 to 2012, the newspaper said.
The stock fell 0.3 percent to 13.32 yuan.  
 PetroChina Co.  (601857 CH): China’s audit office found
irregularities in contracts signed for part of a 142.2 billion
yuan natural gas pipeline being built by PetroChina’s parent
company, China National Petroleum Corp. The stock gained 0.1
percent to 10.77 yuan.  
